body_text.text:
At present, air transport is a booming business despite certain fluctuations in demand caused by international events such as 9/11, Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) and the conflicts in Afghanistan and Iraq. In Germany, in particular, traffic is increasing substantially, and between 1997 and 2015 passenger services are predicted to double (Table 1
). This would mean an increase in air transport’s share of the passenger transport market from 4% to 7% (Table 2
). Such levels of actual and predicted growth have led to numerous enlargements of the infrastructure on the ground. Not only are measures to increase the capacities of airports in German conurbations being taken: the number of airports that can be used by larger jets (more than 100 passengers) will increase significantly across the country. This fact underlines the competitive nature of airport infrastructure provision.
